Pronunciation:
Notes: Spg <i>korakine</i> may be from Hooker??; also spg karakine
Citations
Date:  0/5/2003
Source:  Forest & Bird
Author:
Vol / Page:  No. 308/29
Edition:
Quote:  The [karaka] fruit attracts the native pigeon which must digest the flesh and pass the poisonous kernel whole, before it kills. The poison is known to science as karakin. According to <i>The Poisonous Plants of New Zealand</i> by H.E.Connor, the effect of karakin on humans is to cause 'paralysis preceded by violent spasms and convulsions'.
Notes:

Date:  28/4/2001
Source:  Listener (New Zealand Listener)
Author:
Vol / Page:  40
Edition:
Quote:  There are a lot of trees, with most beautiful names:.. karaka - the flesh of the heavy orange fruit is edible but the seed kernels contain a deadly poison, karakin, that causes convulsions and deformity. Maori steamed and washed the kernels to remove the poison.
Notes:

Date:  0/0/1872
Source:  TrNZi
Author:
Vol / Page:  4/363
Edition:
Quote:  The author [W. Skey] announced that he had succeeded in isolating the bitter principle of the Karaka berry, and had found it to be a crystallizable resin, analogous to the active poisons picrotoxine and digitaline. Mr. Skey proposed to name the new resin `Karakine'.
Notes:

